<quiz><question number="25">
        <prompt>What impact did the Bland-Allison Act of 1878 have?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Required the Treasury to purchase silver for coinage</option>
            <option letter="b">Established the gold standard</option>
            <option letter="c">Created national banks</option>
            <option letter="d">Regulated paper currency</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The Bland-Allison Act required the Treasury to purchase between $2-4 million worth of silver monthly for coinage, representing a compromise in the silver controversy.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question number="26">
        <prompt>What was the significance of the "company town" system?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Gave employers complete control over workers' lives</option>
            <option letter="b">Provided worker independence</option>
            <option letter="c">Created urban development</option>
            <option letter="d">Promoted labor unions</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Company towns allowed employers to control workers' housing, shopping, and social lives, often creating a cycle of debt through company stores and rent.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question number="27">
        <prompt>How did the development of the Westinghouse air brake affect railroads?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Significantly improved railroad safety</option>
            <option letter="b">Increased train speed only</option>
            <option letter="c">Reduced fuel consumption</option>
            <option letter="d">Changed track design</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The Westinghouse air brake revolutionized railroad safety by providing a reliable way to stop trains, reducing accidents and allowing for longer trains.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question number="28">
        <prompt>What was the primary purpose of the American Federation of Labor?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">To organize skilled workers by craft</option>
            <option letter="b">To unite all workers regardless of skill</option>
            <option letter="c">To promote socialist ideals</option>
            <option letter="d">To support political parties</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The AFL focused on organizing skilled workers by craft, pursuing "bread and butter" issues like wages and working conditions rather than broad social reform.</explanation>
